{
  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game centers on trading red and blue chips, which have different private values for each player, while green chips are common-value and therefore strategically simple: everyone values green at $0.50. The key private-value asymmetries are: buffalo values blue highly and red very little (BLUE 0.70, RED 0.10), bear values both blue and red fairly highly (BLUE 1.00, RED 0.60), and goose values both blue and red very little (BLUE 0.10, RED 0.10). Because green is fixed at $0.50 for all, it serves as a natural medium of exchange or safe reference asset, whereas red and blue are the main sources of potential gains from trade. From an efficiency standpoint, the ideal allocation would send most blue chips to bear (the highest blue value) and reasonably many blue chips to buffalo, and send surplus red away from goose and buffalo (who value red only $0.10) toward bear (who values red at $0.60), with goose often acting as a low-value holder willing to trade away blue or red for green. However, the players do not know each other’s exact valuations; they only see their own calculator and observed trading behavior, so they must infer who likes which chip colors by what offers and acceptances appear. Buffalo is numerate, reflective, and highly cooperative; she is likely to look for “mutually good” trades and might use green as a safe currency, but she is also uncertainty-averse and unwilling to sacrifice clear personal value for purely speculative gains. Bear has the strongest marginal value for blue and decent value for red; she may be motivated to accumulate blue and red but faces uncertainty about which partner will respond, so she needs to design proposals that will be accepted by at least one counterpart and still leave her a positive surplus. Goose has low private values for red and blue and the same value for green as others; she is a natural seller of red and blue if she can gain extra green, but being older and reasonably numerate, she may hesitate to make trades that feel risky or complex. Strategic uncertainty comes from three main sources: (1) incomplete information about others’ values; (2) simultaneous acceptance with random partner selection if more than one player accepts; and (3) the limited three-round horizon with one proposal per player each round, which pressures players to make reasonably attractive offers early rather than waiting for perfect information. Overall, the likely pattern is that buffalo and bear try to move away from low-value chips toward higher-value ones (especially blue), while goose tends to sell away red or blue for green when the personal calculator shows a gain. Many low-margin offers will be declined, but some simple, clearly positive-sum trades—especially ones that swap red for green or blue for green in goose’s favor while helping bear or buffalo rebalance—are likely to be accepted.",
