      "round_explanation": "Round 2 is the final opportunity for trading, so players face an endgame environment: they can ignore any dynamic or reputational concerns and focus purely on immediate surplus. By this point, the observed history strongly suggests that goose is consistently happy to give up red or blue for green at modestly unfavorable rates, while bear is willing to acquire red and possibly blue when the calculator shows a clear gain, and buffalo reliably accepts trades that convert red or blue into blue or green when they are positive for her. Buffalo now likely holds a portfolio tilted further toward blue and away from green, bear holds more red and perhaps some additional blue, and goose holds more green but fewer red and blue. Given the impending end of the game, proposals now can be more aggressive but still must show strictly positive surplus to the counterparty; lowball offers will simply be rejected. We expect relatively simple trades, often using green as the payment medium, that exploit known value asymmetries: buffalo or bear offering red to goose for green, bear offering red for blue or vice versa, and goose possibly making one final attempt to convert low-value red or blue into green. Since there is no future beyond this round, players who see a sure small gain will likely accept rather than wait for a better, nonexistent future opportunity.",
