{
  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features symmetric initial endowments (10 RED, 10 BLUE, 10 GREEN each) but asymmetric private values for RED and BLUE. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 to everyone, and there is no time discounting or carryover across games. Because each player sees only their own payoff calculator, they know exactly how any proposed trade affects their own payoff but do not know the others’ dollar values and must infer them from observed behavior.\n\nValue profile and core incentives:\n- badger-red-5032: RED = $0.80, BLUE = $0.80, GREEN = $0.50. Badger values both RED and BLUE more than GREEN. They should be willing to give up GREEN to get either RED or BLUE, and be reluctant to part with RED/BLUE unless they receive at least as much value back.\n- camel-yellow-5577: RED = $0.60, BLUE = $0.40, GREEN = $0.50. Camel likes RED more than GREEN, and GREEN more than BLUE. Camel will want to convert BLUE into RED or GREEN, and might trade away some GREEN for RED if the rate is favorable, but will be less willing to give away RED.\n- squid-yellow-9545: RED = $0.20, BLUE = $0.60, GREEN = $0.50. Squid strongly prefers BLUE and GREEN to RED. Squid will want to trade away RED to get BLUE or GREEN and will hesitate to part with BLUE unless they get even more value back, or unless they see a very favorable multi-step opportunity.\n\nFrom a social-surplus perspective, the highest uses are: RED in the hands of Badger or Camel (0.8 and 0.6) rather than Squid (0.2), BLUE in the hands of Badger or Squid (0.8 and 0.6) rather than Camel (0.4), and GREEN is symmetric at 0.5. Mutual gains exist when, for example, Squid trades low-value RED for GREEN or BLUE, Camel trades low-value BLUE for GREEN or RED, and Badger trades GREEN for either RED or BLUE. However, trades must make both sides individually better off at their private values, and proposers cannot target a specific recipient if multiple players accept. This randomization risk discourages proposals that are good with one counterpart but bad with another.\n\nStrategically, each proposer faces:\n1) Private-value uncertainty: they only see their own surplus calculator, so they must infer others’ valuations from what trades they accept or reject. Early in the game, they may explore with modest offers that seem broadly attractive to at least one counterpart.\n2) Recipient-selection uncertainty: if a proposal is good for multiple players, any of them may accept and the recipient is randomly chosen. This encourages designing offers that are acceptable to whatever counterpart ends up matched, or sufficiently beneficial that even the worst-case counterpart acceptance still yields a gain.\n3) Three-round horizon: with only three rounds and one proposal per player per round, there is limited time to learn or coordinate on complex trades. Players are likely to focus on straightforward, clearly profitable one-step trades (e.g., trading away their least-valued color for a more-valued color) instead of speculative sequences.\n\nGiven the personas, all three players are moderately to highly cooperative but still payoff-maximizing. Camel and Squid display high cognitive and financial literacy, so they are likely to calculate net gains precisely and will rarely accept negative-surplus trades. Badger is somewhat less numerate but still reasonably capable, and with high cooperation orientation may occasionally offer slightly generous terms to increase the chance of acceptance, without sacrificing much value. Across the three rounds, we expect a pattern of early cautious probing, followed by more targeted trades as players infer who likes which colors. Because Squid values RED so little, they are the natural buyer of BLUE and GREEN and seller of RED; Camel is a natural buyer of RED and seller of BLUE; Badger is a natural buyer of both RED and BLUE and seller of GREEN. Many win–win trades involve moving RED away from Squid and BLUE away from Camel toward Badger, often mediated through GREEN.\n\nThe forecast below reconstructs one plausible full trajectory of proposals and accept/reject decisions, assuming each player looks for clearly positive expected value, simple proposals, and avoids offers where the random recipient risk could make the trade negative for them.",
