lculate and pursue modest but clear gains, while Dog is empathetic but more uncertainty-averse and slightly weaker on numeracy, likely to start with simple, easy-to-understand offers and avoid highly risky or complex terms. Because everyone has three proposal turns, we expect some experimentation in early rounds, followed by more targeted offers once players infer that Butterfly strongly values blue, Dog strongly values red, and Ram is relatively weak on both red and blue and more oriented toward safe green holdings. Over three rounds, a likely trajectory is: (1) initial feeler trades revealing who likes which chips, (2) mid-game attempts to exploit perceived comparative advantages (e.g., swapping Dog’s blue for others’ red, or Butterfly’s red/green for others’ blue), and (3) end-game tightening, where players become pickier and only accept clearly positive and strategically aligned trades as the opportunity to adjust portfolios runs out.",
