  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features private values for red and blue chips and a common value for green chips. All players start with 10 of each color. Because green is worth $0.50 to everyone, it functions as a natural benchmark: trades that simply swap green for other colors tend to be zero- or low-risk in value terms. The real bargaining friction comes from red and blue chips, whose private values differ:\n\n- alligator-orange-6315 (Alligator): RED=$0.60, BLUE=$0.50, GREEN=$0.50. Red is Alligator’s best color, but only slightly above green and blue.\n- buffalo-purple-4069 (Buffalo): RED=$0.50, BLUE=$0.20, GREEN=$0.50. Blue is strongly disfavored; red and green are tied and attractive.\n- rabbit-yellow-6681 (Rabbit): RED=$1.00, BLUE=$0.30, GREEN=$0.50. Red is extremely valuable; blue is weak; green is moderate.\n\nEven though players know only their own values, some qualitative structure is common knowledge: ranges for chip prices and the fact that others may value colors differently. Rational responders will accept any proposal that strictly increases their own total dollar value and reject proposals that reduce it. They are indifferent at exactly zero surplus, but in practice most people avoid zero-gain deals unless there is some strategic or signaling motive.\n\nThe main cross-player complementarities likely to shape trade are:\n- Rabbit values red far more than anyone else, so it is efficient for red chips to flow gradually toward Rabbit.\n- Buffalo strongly dislikes blue relative to green and red, so Buffalo is eager to dump blue in exchange for green or red.\n- Alligator is relatively balanced, slightly favoring red, so can profit by arbitraging between Buffalo’s weak blue and someone else’s stronger blue value, or by moving some red to Rabbit if compensated with multiple blue.\n\nUncertainty arises because each player is unsure of others’ exact values and must infer them from which deals are offered and accepted. Over only three rounds (nine proposal turns), players have limited time to explore, so they tend to propose clearly self-profitable trades that they expect at least one partner might plausibly accept based on broad ranges: red is typically at the high end of the 0.10–1.00 band, blue at the low-to-mid, green fixed at 0.50. Since acceptance is simultaneous, proposers must design deals that are attractive to at least one counterpart but also robust to partner uncertainty: if both accept, the partner is chosen at random.\n\nGiven the short horizon and the surplus calculator, most accepted trades will be modest but strictly positive-sum for both sides, with Buffalo offloading blue for red/green, Rabbit gradually acquiring red, and Alligator capturing small arbitrage gains across colors. Declined offers will mostly be those that accidentally ask a high-valuer to give up its best color too cheaply or that offer blue to Buffalo without enough compensation. The following forecast traces one internally consistent realized path of such bargaining dynamics over the three rounds.",
